Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.670 --> 00:00:05.350
Let's say I have some subspace
V, that is a subset of Rn.

00:00:08.100 --> 00:00:10.690
And let's say that we also
have its orthogonal

00:00:10.690 --> 00:00:13.820
complement, we write
that as V perp.

00:00:13.820 --> 00:00:17.410
That'll also be a
subset of Rn.

00:00:17.410 --> 00:00:19.520
A couple of videos ago, it might
have even been the last

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:25.820
video if I remember properly, we
learned that the dimension

00:00:25.820 --> 00:00:31.040
of V, plus the dimension of the
orthogonal complement of

00:00:31.040 --> 00:00:33.850
V, which is also another
subspace, is going

00:00:33.850 --> 00:00:35.220
to be equal to n.

00:00:35.220 --> 00:00:40.880
Remember dimension is just the
number of linearly independent

00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:43.470
vectors you need to have
a basis for V.

00:00:43.470 --> 00:00:46.320
And the dimension here is the
number of linearly independent

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:48.960
vectors you need to have a
basis for the orthogonal

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:50.460
complement of V.

00:00:50.460 --> 00:00:53.410
Now given this, let's see if we
can come up with some other

00:00:53.410 --> 00:00:57.340
interesting ways in which these
two subspaces relate to

00:00:57.340 --> 00:00:57.760
each other.

00:00:57.760 --> 00:01:01.360
Or how they might relate to
all of the vectors in Rn.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:06.250
So the first question is, do
these two subspaces have

00:01:06.250 --> 00:01:07.340
anything in common?

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:10.200
Are there any vectors that are
in common with the two.

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:13.580
And to test whether there is,
let's just assume there is,

00:01:13.580 --> 00:01:17.830
and see what the properties of
that vector would have to be.

00:01:17.830 --> 00:01:25.470
Let's assume right here that I
have some vector x that is a

00:01:25.470 --> 00:01:28.230
member of my subspace V.

00:01:28.230 --> 00:01:32.630
Let's also assume that x is
a member of the orthogonal

00:01:32.630 --> 00:01:33.880
complement of V.

00:01:39.180 --> 00:01:41.590
Now what does this second
statement mean?

00:01:41.590 --> 00:01:51.250
Membership in the orthogonal
complement means that x dot v,

00:01:51.250 --> 00:01:58.050
for any v that is a member of
our subspace, is going to be

00:01:58.050 --> 00:01:58.590
equal to 0.

00:01:58.590 --> 00:02:00.770
Let me write it this
way actually.

00:02:00.770 --> 00:02:07.660
x dot v is equal to 0
for any v that is a

00:02:07.660 --> 00:02:08.860
member of our subspace.

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:11.620
That's what it means to be a
member of V's orthogonal

00:02:11.620 --> 00:02:12.770
complement.

00:02:12.770 --> 00:02:17.130
Now we assume that x is
also a member of V.

00:02:17.130 --> 00:02:20.320
So that means that we can
stick x here as well.

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:22.270
For any member of V.

00:02:22.270 --> 00:02:23.600
x is also a member of V.

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:29.310
So that implies that x
dot x is equal to 0.

00:02:29.310 --> 00:02:36.990
Another way to write that is
that the length of x squared

00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:37.970
is equal to 0.

00:02:37.970 --> 00:02:39.560
Or the length of x
is equal to 0.

00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:41.160
And that's only true
for one vector.

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:43.110
You can even try it out
with the different

00:02:43.110 --> 00:02:46.030
constituents of x.

00:02:46.030 --> 00:02:49.750
The only vector that that's
true for is the 0 vector.

00:02:49.750 --> 00:02:52.770
So x has to be equal
to the 0 vector.

00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:55.320
That's the only vector in Rn
that when you dot it with

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:58.210
itself you get 0, or whose
the square of its

00:02:58.210 --> 00:02:59.750
length is equal to 0.

00:02:59.750 --> 00:03:02.510
And we've shown that many,
many, many videos ago.

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:08.310
What this tells us is at that
the intersection between V and

00:03:08.310 --> 00:03:11.490
V complement-- this kind of
upside down U just means

00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:13.840
intersection, it just means
where do these two sets

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:19.680
overlap-- the only place that
these overlap is with a subset

00:03:19.680 --> 00:03:20.740
of the 0 vector.

00:03:20.740 --> 00:03:23.070
So if I were to draw all
of Rn like this.

00:03:26.770 --> 00:03:28.020
Let's say that this is Rn.

00:03:30.460 --> 00:03:32.820
And let's say I draw
the subspace V.

00:03:39.870 --> 00:03:42.300
And let's say I draw the
orthogonal complement to V.

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:45.440
It's all of these vectors
right here.

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:47.870
This is the orthogonal
complement to V right there.

00:03:47.870 --> 00:03:49.805
So this is V perp.

00:03:54.620 --> 00:03:56.920
These are all of the vectors
that when I dot it with any

00:03:56.920 --> 00:03:58.765
vector here, I'm going
to get equal to 0.

00:03:58.765 --> 00:04:00.050
So this is V perp.

00:04:00.050 --> 00:04:03.410
The intersection, their overlap,
the only vector that

00:04:03.410 --> 00:04:10.030
is a member of both
is the 0 vector.

00:04:10.030 --> 00:04:12.640
That's their only
intersection.

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:13.490
So that's fair enough.

00:04:13.490 --> 00:04:15.900
The only vector that's a member
of a subspace and its

00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:18.500
orthogonal complement
is the 0 vector.

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:20.220
Nothing too profound there.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:22.760
Let's see if we can come up with
some other interesting

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:26.010
relations between the subspace
and its orthogonal complement.

00:04:26.010 --> 00:04:30.240
Maybe some arbitrary
vectors in Rn.

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:33.830
So let's just write down--
well we know that the

00:04:33.830 --> 00:04:41.910
dimension of our subspace
V is equal to k.

00:04:44.470 --> 00:04:47.400
If its equal to k, we know that
its dimension plus its

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:50.230
orthogonal complement has to be
equal to n, because we're

00:04:50.230 --> 00:04:51.480
dealing in Rn.

00:04:54.570 --> 00:04:57.165
And we also know that the
orthogonal complement of V is

00:04:57.165 --> 00:05:00.470
a subset of Rn, I drew
it right here.

00:05:00.470 --> 00:05:03.030
The dimension of V
is equal to k.

00:05:03.030 --> 00:05:04.610
That's a k right there.

00:05:04.610 --> 00:05:13.290
And what's the dimension of the
orthogonal complement of V

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:14.470
going to be?

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:16.420
Well, when you add them
together-- I wrote that up

00:05:16.420 --> 00:05:18.720
here-- they have to equal n.

00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:22.100
So this guy's going to
have to be n minus k.

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:24.380
If you have k here.

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:27.310
This guy's dimension is k, this
guy's dimension right

00:05:27.310 --> 00:05:30.840
here if, it's n minus k, that
when you add these two up, k

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:33.930
plus n minus k is going
to be equal to n.

00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:36.760
So this guy will have a
dimension of n minus k.

00:05:36.760 --> 00:05:38.100
Now what does dimension mean?

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:41.300
It means that that's the number
of linearly independent

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:44.690
vectors you need to
form a basis.

00:05:44.690 --> 00:05:48.720
I have k vectors as
a basis for V.

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:56.540
I have v1, v2, all
the way to vk.

00:05:56.540 --> 00:06:03.940
And this is a basis for V, which
just means they're all

00:06:03.940 --> 00:06:05.210
linearly independent.

00:06:05.210 --> 00:06:06.500
And they span V.

00:06:06.500 --> 00:06:09.850
Any member of V right here can
be represented as a linear

00:06:09.850 --> 00:06:13.070
combination of these vectors.

00:06:13.070 --> 00:06:16.750
Now the dimension of the
orthogonal complement of

00:06:16.750 --> 00:06:17.965
V is n minus k.

00:06:17.965 --> 00:06:20.550
So we could have n
minus k vectors.

00:06:20.550 --> 00:06:31.030
Let's call them w1, w2, all
the way to wn minus k.

00:06:31.030 --> 00:06:33.600
We have n minus k of
these characters.

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:41.020
And this set is a basis
for the orthogonal

00:06:41.020 --> 00:06:42.260
complement of V.

00:06:42.260 --> 00:06:45.250
So any vector in here can be
represented as a linear

00:06:45.250 --> 00:06:47.560
combination of these
guys right here.

00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:49.355
And all of these guys are
linearly independent.

00:06:49.355 --> 00:06:53.030
So you don't have any redundant
vectors there.

00:06:53.030 --> 00:06:55.110
Now let's explore.

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:56.640
And I'll tell you where
I'm trying to go.

00:06:56.640 --> 00:07:00.830
I'm trying to see if I combine
these two sets, whether I get

00:07:00.830 --> 00:07:02.860
a basis for all of Rn.

00:07:02.860 --> 00:07:05.390
That's what I'm trying
